post_text: Welcome to the official Galt Joint Union High School District Facebook page! We are excited to utilize this page to easily get information about our high schools and our district out to the community. We will be posting frequently on this page about things that are affecting our students, as well as sharing updates about the exciting things we are doing at all three school sites. We encourage current and future parents of students to follow this page for up-to-date news and announcements! We also encourage you to follow our individual school site Facebook pages for individualized updates from the schools.

Thank you!

Galt JUHSD Families...please help us with this survey so we can better help you with your needs!

In light of the changes that we have all endured over the past month and a half due to COVID-19, the Galt JUHSD wants to check in with our families to see how you and your children are navigating these difficult times and learn how we, as a school district, could further support you and your family. Please take a few minutes to complete our Community Needs Survey. If we have your email on file you should have received an email from Panorama Education with a link to the survey. If you did not receive this email, you can still take the survey by going to https://surveys.panoramaed.com/galt. Use the Access Code: 3620671789 to start the survey.

text: Message from the Superintendent - March 20, 2020

post_text:
Hello Families of Galt JUHSD:

We ask that all of our students please take an online survey that can be found at the district website at www.GHSD.us as soon as possible.

This survey will ask you questions about the availability of computer and internet access in your home. We are working hard to provide online education for all of our students during the school closure, and for those who do not have computer and internet access in their homes, to provide those as best we can. Please take the simple online survey as soon as you can. Again, the survey can be found at www.GHSD.us.

Thank you,

William Spalding
Superintendent

The Galt Herald
February 6 at 11:14 PM ·

The high school board just recognized the district IT team for doing an outstanding job keeping the district up and running.
IT director Kevin Clemons said “having a team like this is a dream. And they even all like each other!”
Clemons gave a report on all the great things the IT team is working on including cyber security upgrades.
Board president Dan Denier said that the IT team is like first responders, when a teacher or staff member hits the “panic button”, IT is right there.
Speaking to the team, Denier said “you are a valuable part of the district.”

post_text: The Liberty Ranch cheerleaders are heading to UCA High School Nationals in Florida this week. Hundreds of high schools across the nation attend this competition and the Liberty ladies will be competing against almost 40 other schools in their category. The last time Galt cheerleaders competed at Nationals was 14 years ago in Texas. Their first competition is this Friday at the ESPN complex in Florida. Wish them and their dedicated coaches, Barbara and Alexis Welch luck!

post_text:
Liberty Ranch High School Sculpture Teacher, Shanee Best, and her students made and presented this beautiful artwork to Mr. Bill Roper at R&M Electric. In 2017, the art department was donated an older kiln but we did not have the right electrical outlet to install it. R&M Electric not only donated all of the electrical materials to get this kiln plugged in and working, but they also donated their valuable time to run the wires, go through the walls and attic. From our understanding, this is not the first time Bill and his crew have donated to both GHS and LRHS.

In August, the VAPA department was able to purchase a new kiln to replace the older unreliable version, and with the generous help of R&M Electric, we were able to install this new kiln at a reasonable cost.

We would like to thank R&M Electric, but also the many other businesses and individuals who donate and help our schools. Please know the teachers and staff are so grateful.

Being named to the honor roll isn’t just for our students!
Galt Joint Union High School District earned a spot on the College Board’s 10th Annual AP® District Honor Roll. The honor roll recognizes school districts in the United States and Canada that have expanded access to Advanced Placement® coursework and maintained or increased the percentage of students earning scores of 3 or higher on AP Exams. https://apcentral.collegeboard.org/pdf/ap-district-honor-roll-10th-annual.pdf

post_text: Our hearts go out to the many people that Mr. Nunes influenced. He will be dearly missed by those of us at GJUHSD.
shared_text:
Galt Liberty Unified Ensembles
October 13, 2017 at 10:20 AM · Galt, CA ·

It is with a heavy heart that I inform that you Mr. Nunes, our drama teacher, passed away last evening. I know this is a very difficult time for all of us as Mr. Nunes was an outstanding teacher, and father. He will be dearly missed.

Today, we will have grief counseling available in the library for any staff or students needing to speak to a counselor.

This is a difficult time for all of us but we are a family here at Galt and Liberty Ranch High Schools and we must stick together and comfort one another in this difficult time.

Thank you

At LRHS, we know how important reading skills are. We are proud of the progress our students have made this year! We saw a 12% increase in the percent of our students that were at or above grade level from August to May. 330 students met our district's goal of 1300+ lexile points and 361 students made a growth of 100+ lexile points! Congratulations Hawks!

We are excited to see that in May, 9% more students were at or above grade level than in August. We also had 199 students reach our district goal of 1300+ lexile points and 206 students saw a growth of 100+ lexile points! Great job Warriors!

post_text:
Our teachers have been working hard to help our students to achieve growth in their reading ability and comprehension. We are proud to announce that we saw growth at all grade levels, with the most growth happening in 9th grade! We also saw an increase in the percent of students who were at or above grade level.
This analysis is based on lexile tests given in August 2016 and in May 2017.
